note.text:
Reason For Referral:
To assay for the presence of mutations in the IGHV gene.
Conclusion:
The IGHV region of the clonal B cell population in this
PERIPHERAL BLOOD sample received from was MUTATED.
The sequence of the IGHV fragment of the clonal B cell
population detected here is % homologous to the germline
form of this allele. And IGHV locus of less than 98%
homology is considered mutated (Hamblin et al 1999, Blood,
94:1848-1854).
Analysis:
Next generation bidirectional sequencing of all amplifiable
IGHV regions using "leader" (upstream of FR1) and joining
(J) region PCR primers was done with the Illumina MiSeq
platform and the InVivoScribe LymphoTrack IGHV Leader
Somatic Hypermutation Kit. IGHV sequence analysis and
comparison to germline sequences was done using the
InVivoScribe LymphoTrack IGH SHM MiSeq software to assess
the percentage of sequence variability.
Interpretation:
IGHV mutational testing assesses the percentage of sequence
variability between the V region of the immunoglobin heavy
chain gene in a clonal B cell population compared to the
homologous germline V region sequence.
The clonal B cell population detected here bears the type
of IgH gene rearrangement. The sequence of this fragment is
% homologous to the unmutated (germline) form of this
allele. An IGHV locus of less than 98% homology is
considered mutated, (Hamblin et al 1999, Blood,
94:1848-1854). A mutated allele predicts a better disease
prognosis for CLL and SLL. Clinical correlation is required.

IGHV regions using "leader" (upstream of FR1) and joining
(J) region PCR primers was done with the Illumina MiSeq
platform and the InVivoScribe LymphoTrack IGHV Leader
Somatic Hypermutation Kit. IGHV sequence analysis and
comparison to germline sequences was done using the
InVivoScribe LymphoTrack IGH SHM MiSeq software to assess
the percentage of sequence variability.
Interpretation:
IGHV mutational testing assesses the percentage of sequence
variability between the V region of the immunoglobin heavy
chain gene in a clonal B cell population compared to the
homologous germline V region sequence.
The clonal B cell population detected here bears the type
of IgH gene rearrangement. The sequence of this fragment is
% homologous to the unmutated (germline) form of this
allele. An IGHV locus of greater than 98% homology is
considered unmutated, (Hamblin et al 1999, Blood,
94:1848-1854). An unmutated allele predicts a worse disease
prognosis in CLL and SLL. Clinical correlation is required.
